      'result': """The CVE-2025-55182 vulnerability, widely known as "React2Shell," is a critical unauthenticated remote code execution (RCE) flaw affecting React Server Components (RSC). Disclosed on December 3, 2025, it has been assigned a CVSS v3.x score of 10.0 and a CVSS v4 score of 9.3, indicating its maximum severity.

The vulnerability stems from an unsafe deserialization flaw within React's Flight protocol, which is used to handle server component payloads. This flaw allows attackers to craft malicious payloads that, when processed by the server, can execute arbitrary code with the privileges of the user running the affected web server process. Exploitation is straightforward, requiring only a single, specially crafted HTTP request without the need for authentication, user interaction, or elevated permissions.

React2Shell impacts React versions 19.0.0 through 19.2.0 and numerous popular frameworks that implement React Server Components, including Next.js, React Router, and Waku, as well as any bundler or plugin that integrates RSC. The vulnerability exists under the default configurations of these frameworks, making a significant number of systems exposed and vulnerable.

Following its disclosure, Google Threat Intelligence Group (GTIG) observed widespread and rapid exploitation of CVE-2025-55182 by a diverse range of threat actors. This includes financially motivated cybercrime groups deploying cryptocurrency miners like XMRig and suspected espionage groups, such as China-nexus threat clusters like Earth Lamia (UNC5454) and Jackpot Panda, targeting victim networks globally. Publicly available exploits are actively being used in the wild, underscoring the immediate need for organizations to prioritize patching all affected React and Next.js assets."""
    }
  )
)] role='user'
